🛑 Don't Stop 'til You Get Enough: Reliable Sequential Testing with Precision and Conclusiveness as Goals

Objectives. Sequential hypothesis testing offers flexibility over fixed-sample designs,
but coupling stopping rules to decision criteria — such as p-value thresholds or
posterior-based heuristics — risks confirmation bias from early, unrepresentative samples.
"Precision is the Goal" (PitG), proposed by Kruschke (2015), eliminates this bias by
halting only once a pre-specified posterior precision is reached, then applying the
Highest Density Interval + Region of Practical Equivalence (HDI+ROPE) decision rule.
We identify a key limitation: PitG frequently yields inconclusive outcomes when the null
hypothesis is true — precisely the regime required by confirmatory applications such as bioequivalence testing, software regression validation, and policy evaluation.

Methods. We propose "Enhanced Precision is the Goal" (ePitG), which requires both the
precision target and a conclusive hypothesis outcome — accepting or rejecting the null —
to be satisfied simultaneously before stopping. This conservative recoupling retains the
near-zero false-positive rate of PitG while substantially improving decisiveness. We
evaluate both methods through binomial simulations across a range of true parameter values.

Results & Conclusions. In fair coin experiments (θ_true = θ_null = 0.5) with precision
goal ω_goal = 0.08, PitG yields 63.3% inconclusive outcomes; ePitG reduces this to 2.3%
at a median cost of only 4.7% more samples, with zero false positives. Crucially, unlike
NHST, the HDI+ROPE framework also permits positive acceptance of the null — essential
for confirmatory applications. A closed-form expression for the minimal expected stopping sample size enables prospective planning without simulation. Open-source code and an interactive online planning calculator are provided to support adoption.
